notesStmt.note: Incipit: Par ce moien voisineuf eur nom / ne depuis ... (f. 1r).
The name Richard appears at the end of the work (f. 139v) in a hand that may be contemporary but does not appear elsewhere in the work.

msIdentifier.repository: Kislak Center for Special Collections, Rare Books and Manuscripts

msContents.summary: The history of the city of Metz written in quatrains, including the establishment of the city; stories about St. Clement, the first bishop; accounts of numerous battles in the region; and actions of Henry II of France and Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor, towards the town.

supportDesc.extent: 139 leaves : 200 x 150 (173 x 77) mm. bound to 208 x 170 mm
supportDesc.foliation: Paper, ii (19th-century paper) + 139 + ii (19th-century paper); 1, 7, [i], 10-14, 29-126, 129-161; contemporary foliation in ink, upper right recto, [1-139], modern foliation in pencil, lower center recto. References in this record are to the modern foliation.

layoutDesc.layout: Written in 5 or 6 quatrains per page; frame-ruled in ink.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in several different cursive scripts, with quatrains in one hand, section headings and marginal dates in another, and the entries for 1554 through 1576 (f. 105v-139v) in a third hand.

binding.p: 19th-century calf (Zacour-Hirsch); spine is partly missing and is detached from upper cover.

history.provenance: Formerly owned by Hermann Sucher (bookplate, inside upper cover).
Sold by Bernard M. Rosenthal (New York, N. Y.), cat. I (1954), Item 70.28.
